Analyzing ACL Tear Data to Discover Demographic, Injury, Diagnosis, and Information Trends

Marisa Ricci and Matthew Scherp

Hyperlink to github webpage: https://matthewbubble.github.io/

Project Description

Our project is an analysis of data relating to ACL tears. Both of us play soccer and ACL tears are both incredibly common and take a very long time to recover from so we wanted to do an analyis to find correlations between different variables and ACL tears. If people are more aware of the causes of ACL tears they can prevent and diagnose them better. Additionally, to definitively diagnose an ACL tear, arthroscopy must be used. However, this is a surgery and if the tear was initially misdiagnosed this procudedure would be done for no reason (the goal is to repair the tear). If we could build a model to more accurately predict the likelihood of a tear noninvasively, this expensive procedure could be bypassed except in cases where it is necessary for the ACL repair.

Collaboration Plan

We are in every class together and also work the same on campus job. Currently, we plan to meet on each other's shifts, for at least 2-3 hours a week, but up to 8 if needed. We have set up our GitHub repository to share information and are sharing a Colab notebook to update coding for our dataset. We also each have copies of the Colab notebooks and can commit the changes to the master which reduces the possibility of changes getting overwritten if we are working at the same time. We also have each picked a data set to be the "expert" in and as we had more data sets we will likely continue to specialize. However, we are checking in with each other and giving the other person suggestions for other interesting elements to work on in their data.

Project Goals

By the end of this project we want to have found statistical relationships in our ACL data relating to diagnosis, demographics, and injury mechanism. While we can't draw any causation related conclusions from statistical correlations, we can see potential avenues for further research.

Final Question

What are the factors that affect a person's likelihood to tear their ACL and how can it be diagnosed the easiest?

Data Collection (Datasets)¶

This first dataset (labeled "ACL2"), includes a lot of relevant information regarding the patients and their injuries, such as previous surgeries, the cause of injury, age, sex, knee, and severity of the injury. With this dataset, we hope to answer some questions about what types of movements and/or sports cause the most ACL tears. For example, do factors outside of exclusive movement create other additional risks to tearing the ACL, or maybe even age and gender?

ACL3 is a questionnaire dataset that is relevant to the awareness of ACL tears and what people believe are factors causing these tears. We think this will be a good dataset to understand how/where people are finding out about ACL tears and how common and severe it is. While we won't be building our model off of this dataset, we can use it to compare our model to what people believe are factors in ACL tears and see how informed the general public is.

Data Processing, Exploratory Analysis, and Visualization¶

Mechanism of Injury¶

To begin answering our investigation question we started by investigating mechanism of injury using the ACL2 dataset.

Mechanism of injury was likely noted by a doctor and the notes are not consistent (some are more detailed than others). To make more distict categories (although there will still be many), general categories were first combined or standardized. Next specific categories (e.g. soccer, vehicle accident) were allowed to overwrite the more general categories to get a better idea of what actually caused the potential ACL injury. From this data, we were able to generate a graph that showed what geneally causes a potential ACL tear.

In [9]:

causes_df = ACL2[["mechanism of injury"]]

These counts were not entirely helpful because a potential ACL tear is not a confirmed ACL tear so a new dataframe was created that took whether an ACL was actually torn into account. The proportion of potential ACL tears that were confirmed ACL tears were also calculated.

# group by category to calculate count of incidents and proportion of torn ACLs
torn_acl_summary = causes_results.groupby('category').agg(
    Incident_Count=('Torn ACL from Arthroscopy', 'size'),
    Proportion_Torn_ACL=('Torn ACL from Arthroscopy', 'mean')
).reset_index()

# sort by proportion to see categories most associated with a torn ACL at top
torn_acl_summary = torn_acl_summary.sort_values(by='Proportion_Torn_ACL', ascending=False)

As for factors considered in ACL tears, weight and flexibility were among the highest. These are not very surprising as flexibility and less weight strain both definitely help ligament movement and preventative tears. We did find that higher weight was correlated to more ACL tears so public perception matched the data in this case.

However, to test this theory, we took the most important factor considered, weight, and used the ACL4 dataset to determine how accurate this was. To determine, this, we compared the weight of the players against the severity of their ACL injuries. If weight is a significant factor, then the higher the severity of the injury should related to the higher weight of a player.

To test this, we took every player from each severity and took the average weights of the players from these severities and graphed it below.

In [17]:
ACL4.groupby(["Injury_Severity"])["Weight_kg"].mean().plot.bar(ylabel = "Weight (kg)", title = "Weight vs Injury Severity")
Out[17]:
<Axes: title={'center': 'Weight vs Injury Severity'}, xlabel='Injury_Severity', ylabel='Weight (kg)'>

As can be seen, weight is actually slightly higher in the mild category, with the moderate and severe being quite similar. This shows that weight is not necessarily a signficant factor, based on the data. However, this could also be skewed by the lack of large number of players, allowing outliers to how more influence. Additionally, a lot of basketball players have a lot of similar builds, potentially causing the similarity in weights. Though, there are no significant differences in weight vs severity of the ACL tear observed.

Injury Diagnosis¶

ACL tears can be diagnosed in three ways with arthroscopy being the gold standard (as stated in the ACL2 introduction). However, ACL2 also provided information on whether the Lachman test was postive, whether the doctor believed the patient had a torn ACL, and if the MRI showed a torn ACL. These factors were able to be compared to the gold standard test to determine their relative accuracies.

To read more about the different ACL tests and the fact that arthroscopy is the gold standard, see the paper Diagnostic Accuracy of Non-invasive Tests Versus Arthroscopy in Anterior Cruciate Ligament (ACL) Injuries

Link: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38910689/

accuracy = {}
for column in diagnosis_df.columns[:-1]:  # exclude 'Torn ACL from Arthroscopy' column
    correct_predictions = (diagnosis_df[column] == diagnosis_df["Torn ACL from Arthroscopy"]).sum()
    accuracy[column] = correct_predictions / len(diagnosis_df)

It turns out that in this case ACL MRIs were equally as accurate as ACL arthroscopy at diagnosing ACL tears. The Lachman test was the least likely by still had a relatively high accuracy at 94%. The Lachman test is also the easiest and requires the least equipment. For further reading and a video on a Lachman test being performed see this Physiopedia article: https://www.physio-pedia.com/Lachman_Test.

Since the Lachman test is an inexpensive, easy, and relatively accurate way to diagnose an ACL tear, this will be the factor of choice for our model.

Analysis and Hypothesis Testing (Models)¶

K-Nearest Neighbors Models¶

We decided we wanted to make a k-nearest neighbors model based on sports vs non sports, sex, age, and what the Lachman injury diagnosis was. The goal of this model was to better predict noninvasively whether a potential ACL tear would be confirmed by ACL arthroscopy.

First, we created a new dataframe with the information we needed:

In [30]:
# select columns from ACL2 and causes_results dataframes
selected_columns_cr = causes_results[['type']]  # from causes_results
selected_columns_acl2 = ACL2[['Lachman injured', 'Age', 'sex','Torn ACL from Arthroscopy']]  # from ACL2

# concatenate columns horizontally
knn_df = pd.concat([selected_columns_cr, selected_columns_acl2], axis=1)
knn_df

To perform the KNN classification, we first one hot end encoded the columns 'sex' and 'type' because they were originally categorical. Next we added them to the original dataframe and selected our features of interest. In this case this was age, sex, lachman result, and type of injury (sport vs non sport related). To make a better model we chose to use a k cross fold validation and we used 5 cross folds.

In [32]:
# one hot encoded columns for 'sex' and 'type' without dropping original columns
sex_encoded = pd.get_dummies(knn_df['sex'], prefix='sex')
type_encoded = pd.get_dummies(knn_df['type'], prefix='type')

# concatenate one hot encoded columns with original dataframe
knn_df = pd.concat([knn_df, sex_encoded, type_encoded], axis=1)

# select features (X) and target (y) (exclude original 'sex' and 'type')
X = knn_df[['Lachman injured', 'Age'] + list(sex_encoded.columns) + list(type_encoded.columns)]  # features
y = knn_df['Torn ACL from Arthroscopy']  # target

# initialize knn classifier
knn_model = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=3)

# k fold cross validation
cv_scores = cross_val_score(knn_model, X, y, cv=5)
print(f'Accuracy: {np.mean(cv_scores):.4f}')

Accuracy: 0.6072

Our model was only 65% accurate at predicting a positive vs negative ACL tear but we created a confusion matrix to visualize the results.

This finally led us to make an overall correlation matrix that compared the correlation of the anthroscopy test to sex, type of injury, and the lachman test all into one for easier visuals.

In [38]:
# re-encode categorical columns
sex_encoded_full = pd.get_dummies(knn_df['sex'], prefix='sex', drop_first=False)
type_encoded_full = pd.get_dummies(knn_df['type'], prefix='type', drop_first=False)

# create dataframe specifically for correlation matrix
knn_df_for_corr = pd.concat([
    knn_df[['Lachman injured', 'Age', 'Torn ACL from Arthroscopy']],  # numeric and target columns
    sex_encoded_full,  # one-hot encoding sex
    type_encoded_full  # one-hot encoding type
], axis=1)

# correlation matrix
correlation_matrix = knn_df_for_corr.corr()

# show correlation matrix
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt='.2f', cbar=True)
plt.title('Correlation Matrix of ACL Diagnostic Measures')
plt.show()

As can be seen with the torn ACL from Arthroscopy row, the only correlating factors are the lachman injured and the sports related injury. Though the sports related is not significant enough to determine if it is an ACL tear. This also shows how accurate the lachman test is overall, without being invasive as the arthroscopy test.

Overall, the combination of the previous three models, with the final overall model, answered our central questions. First, our data suggests that the main factor that effects if a person tore their ACL was if it was torn playing a sport and the simplest way to get a relatively accurate diagnosis would the Lachman test. While the sports factor seems to be correlated, the accuracy of the Lachman test is actually better on its own (95%) than with the sports factor (86.5%). However, this is a fairly small data set so the numbers are close enough together that it would be worth further investigation with a larger dataset.

To answer our second question, age initially seemed like a logical factor in likelihood of a postive ACL tear. After all, muscles and ligaments tend to weaken as we age making them more prone to tearing. However, using age as a factor significantly reduced the accuracy of our classifier and mainly had the issue of predicting no tear when there was a tear.

Insight¶

We then changed these percentages into counts and grouped them by factors that might be relevant vs irrelevant for sports players since these factors are most related to mechanism of injury (which we broadly categorized into sports vs non sports mechanisms).

To interpret these results we can think back to the mechanism of injury analysis earlier. The fact that 'No Inciting Event' didn't result in any ACL tears and the postive correlation between sports and ACL injuries seems to provide evidence against factors like weak hamstings and quadriceps being large factors in ACL tears. Sports players tend to have strong leg muscles and if those were a significant factor athletes would likely not be getting them at such a high rate. Additionally, sports players also tend to be balanced and flexible and again, those are the highest proportion of ACL tears. It seems like the public perception is inaccurate in this case although, as stated previously, we are limited by the size of our datasets.

Conclusion¶

The central questions that we aimed to investigate with this analysis were:

  1. What are the factors that affect a person's likelihood to tear their ACL?

  2. How can ACL tears be diagnosed the easiest?

These two questions are very related and often the analysis was able to provide insight into both of them. We also wanted to undestand factors that could reasonably be perceived as related to ACL tears but actually were not correlated.

We followed the steps of the data lifecycle to produce this tutorial and conclusions:

  1. Data Collection- We first found and loaded datasets that contained pertinent data about ACL tears. One of the datasets didn't contain ACL tear data but rather awareness data and we chose to use that to make deeper conclusions.

  2. Data Processing (ETL) and Exploratory Analysis & Data Visualization (EDA)- Three categeories of factors were isolated to be studied: injury mechanism, method of diagnosis, and demographic factors. From injury mechanism we were able to see that sports related injuries have a much higher proportion of confirmed ACL tears (70% vs 26%). This data was deemed useful for answering both our central questions. Within method of diagnosis, we studied the methods and accuracy by which ACL tears are diagnosed and determined that the simplest method (Lachman Test) was also fairly accurate. This fed into our second question. Finally, we investigated demographic factors such as age, sex, height, and weight. We noted a trend higher weights and lower ages tended to have more ACL tears. Females also had a slightly higher potential to confirmed tear proportion. This data again could be used to inform both of our questions.

  3. Analysis and Hypothesis Testing (Models)- Based on the data collected in our ETL and EDA section we decided to build k-nearest neighbors classification models and test the accuracy of various combinations of factors. From this we learned that age tends to mislead the classifier dramatically (only 65% accurate) and sex tends to do the same although to a lesser extend (79%). The best combination was just a Lachman test and the knowledge of whether the injury was sustained during sports or not (86.5%). However, this was all still lower than the Lachman test on its own (95%) so adding additional variables to attempt actually made the overall diagnostic ability worse. Despite this, we were still able to conclude that sports were highly correlated to ACL tears (which was not extremely surprising). Since our dataset was small, it is worth further investigation in a larger study about the usefulness of sports as a diagnostic tool. Our second type of model we built was a regression model and it was for height and weight compared to a confirmed ACL tear. The R squared value of the best fit line was very low (0.14) but the trend was positive so while we can't use this model for classification, it also could be an avenue for further study.

  4. Insight- Finally, to add interest to the data, the ACL awareness dataset was used to compare the general public's perception of causes to our results. We found that the public's prediction of weight being a cause matched the correlation we found. However, ultimately the public tended to place emphasis on attributes that wouldn't be relevant for sports players such as lack of flexibility or weak muscles. After grouping the stated factors in sport and non sport factors, a significant proportion of factors were found to be irrelevant if relevancy was solely based on our correlations.

In short to answer the questions, an injury sustained during sports is the factor that is correlated the strongest to a positive ACL tear, while other believed factors such as weight may not have as significant of an impact. However, there may be other factors that can be significant that are not able to be tested at this time. As for the second question, the Lachman test is the easiest and most accurate way to diagnose an ACL tear because other factors simply become confounding variables. While age and sex might have seemed like plausible diagnositic tools, they significantly reduced the overall model accuracy.

As stated many times before, there was not large volumes of ACL data readily available so these correlations were based off of a very small sample size. However, it should be a good example of how data can be collected, processed, visualized, and modeled.
